         <abstract>
            <p>Let $\Delta ABC$ be a triangle with vertices $A, B$ and $C$. It is "bisected" as follows: choose a/the longest side (say $AB$) of $\Delta ABC$, let $D$ be the midpoint of $AB$, then replace $\Delta ABC$ by two triangles, $\Delta ADC$ and $\Delta DBC$. Let $\Delta_{01}$ be a given triangle. Bisect $\Delta_{01}$ into two triangles $\Delta_{11}, \Delta_{12}$. Next, bisect each $\Delta_{1i}, i = 1, 2$, forming four new triangles $\Delta_{2i}, i = 1, 2, 3, 4$. Continue thus, forming an infinite sequence $T_j, j = 0, 1, 2,\ldots,$ of sets of triangles, where $T_j = \{\Delta_{ji}: 1 \leqslant i \leqslant 2^j\}$. It is known that the mesh of $T_j$ tends to zero as $j \rightarrow \infty$. It is shown here that if $\Delta_{01}$ satisfies any of four certain properties, the rate of convergence of the mesh to zero is much faster than that predicted by the general case.</p>
          </abstract>
